iginal except removed substrings. The original whitespace between tags (like newline and spaces) should remain because we didn't touch them. However the output shows that the newlines after <head> and before </head> are gone, and the indentation is missing. Let's compare original: after <head> there is newline and spaces, then title, then newline, then script tags, then newline, then </head>. After removing script tags, we have newline and spaces, title, newline, newline? Wait we removed script tags but left the newline after them? The script tags were on separate lines. Removing them leaves empty lines? Actually the script tags were on lines with leading spaces. Removing the entire line would delete those lines? The regex matches across lines because DOTALL flag matches newline characters as part of .*?, but we only match from '<script...>' up to '</script>' including newlines inside. That will remove the entire content between those tags, but the newline characters outside the tags remain? Let's test by printing original lines. But we need to preserve formatting exactly. Perhaps we should use a parser that can output with minimal changes. However we can try to improve regex to not affect whitespace outside the matched pattern. Instead of removing the whole match, we could replace with empty string, which removes the matched characters, including newlines inside the script tags. That's okay because script tags' internal newlines are part of the script content. But the newline after the opening tag and before closing tag are also inside the match, so they will be removed, causing adjacent lines to merge? In our case, script tags were on separate lines with indentation. The opening tag had newline after '>'? Actually the line: '    <script>alert('xss');</script>' all on one line. So newline before and after the line remains. The line is removed entirely, leaving empty line? The regex removed the whole line content, leaving the leading spaces and newline? Wait the leading spaces are before '<script', not part of the match because pattern starts with '<script'. So leading spaces remain, resulting in a line with just spaces. That line will be blank but with spaces. When we write back, those spaces remain, but they may be collapsed? Let's examine with cat -A. We'll create a test with cat -v to see spaces and newlines.\nBetter approach: Use a more sophisticated method: parse with html.parser but keep original formatting by processing the raw string and marking positions. Could be complex.\nWe can try to adjust regex to capture surrounding whitespace and keep it? Actually we can match the script tag and its inner content, and replace with empty string, leaving surrounding whitespace as is. That's what we did. However the whitespace before the tag is not part of match, so it stays. That's fine.\nBut why formatting changed? Let's examine the raw output more precisely. Use cat -e to show line endings. Let's do that now.",
